ce:section.ce:para:
The current study describes the utility of β-CD functionalized eco-friendly C-dots as the electrode material to accelerate the charge transfer process between the sensing interface and electrode and promote electrode reaction. Herein, we report a sensitive and selective electrochemical sensing platform based on β-CD functionalized C-dots modified electrode (
                     Scheme 1

                     ). It is realized by utilizing the analyte-capturing ability of β-CD and higher surface area and excellent electrical conductivity of C-dots to enhance the sensing performance for electrochemical quantification of LAP. C-dots were prepared by a green synthetic approach i.e. one-pot hydrothermal carbonization, without passivation of any chemicals using the zero-cost, non-toxic, and economically viable green precursor, neem (Azadirachta indica) leaves as raw materials. The β-CDs were appended onto C-dots via hydrogen bonding. Electrode material (β-CD@C-dots) was characterized by TEM, XRD, UV–Vis, fluorescence, FTIR, TGA, electrochemical impedance, and cyclic voltammetry. The performance of the developed electrochemical sensor was checked in terms of reproducibility and repeatability. The practical applicability of the proposed method for the determination of LAP was corroborated in pharmaceutical formulations and biological fluids. The proposed electrochemical sensor presented satisfactory selectivity, long-time stability, and excellent reproducibility.

Further, proposed electroanalytical methods (using β-CD@C-dots/GCE) were validated by evaluating the values of analytical characteristics, the limit of quantification (LOQ = 10 s/m), and the limit of detection (LOD = 3 s/m). The values of LOD and LOQ are calculated and tabulated in Table 2
                        , confirming the sensitivity of the proposed methods. LOD value of 1.81x10-10 mol L-1 was achieved in the present method (
                        Table 2
                        ) which is much lower than the reported value of 3.51 × 10−9 mol L−1 
                        (
                        Table 3

                        ). Among the proposed three methods, the SWV method showed improved sensitivity because its contribution of charging current to the background current is quite lower than that for DPV and LSV methods (Table 2
                        ). A lower detection limit was observed for the SWV method compared to those of DPV and LSV methods. Better sensitivity was noticed at β-CD@C-dots as an inclusion complex was formed and increased the surface area. This facilitated the easy electron transfer at the electrode surface. RSD values were evaluated for inter-day and an intra-day assay of LAP by SWV and the corresponding results are listed in Table 2. RSD values less than 3.5 % highlighted the reproducibility of the results in the determination of LAP in pharmaceutical dosage forms and biological samples.
